  "scopeNotes": [
    "Tree felling and support collapse are multi-block experiences with different authority models. Tag 9 reconstructs one generated tree inside the Chunk Program; support topology is a client proposal submitted through ordinary tag 5 and reward-bearing tag 8 instructions.",
    "Tree tag 9 begins its program-side scan at the submitted cut height. The current client planner begins at its locally discovered trunk base, so a non-base hit can produce different planned and accepted sets.",
    "Tree tag 9 checks the clicked coordinate for an existing broken record but appends other reconstructed tree coordinates without a duplicate lookup. A later lower cut can revisit already-recorded upper coordinates.",
    "Tree tag 9 receives no FoundationChunk, ResourceDropTable, or SurfaceDecorationTable account. It therefore does not apply the corresponding foundation-protection or secondary-drop paths.",
    "Every strict tree reward is appended inside the one instruction. Any failed strict append or later error rolls back the whole transaction, while a successful instruction adds Precision Gathering XP once per reward.",
    "Support collapse first commits the primary tag 8 transaction, then submits at most two canonical block verifications per later transaction. Each transaction is atomic, but the sequence is not.",
    "The program checks each support-collapse coordinate against canonical terrain, prior broken state, mineability, session authority, and foundation protection. It does not receive or validate graph adjacency, support anchors, reach from the primary block, or one shared collapse identity.",
    "A failed two-coordinate collapse batch is retried as two single-coordinate submissions. If neither single succeeds, the current helper aborts the remaining sequence regardless of whether the failures reflect a shared outage or two independent coordinate conflicts.",
    "The current local Chunk and Game artifacts match the finalized deployed ELF prefixes at the captured slot. Both retain the recorded upgrade authority, and this parity does not establish a reproducible build from the dirty worktree or future immutability.",
    "The recent transaction window is an observation with anchored signatures and slots, not an exhaustive history. Zero observed tag 9 instructions must not be interpreted as proof of non-use."
  ]
